Around 200 countries and territories have had at least one case.
Due to the pandemic in Europe, many countries in the Schengen area have restricted free movement and established border controls.
National reactions have included containment measures, such as quarantines (known as stay-at-home orders, on-site refugee orders or confinement) and curfews. As of April 2, about 300 million people, or about 90% of the population, are serving some form of confinement in the United States, more than 50 million people are confined to South Africa, and about 59 million people are confined to the Philippines.
As of March 26, 1,700 million people around the world were in some form of confinement, which increased to 2,600 million people two days later, about a third of the world’s population.
